Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat
#oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry all produce. Place @butter{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP
for 4) in a #small bowl{}; bring to room temperature. Peel and dice
@Yukon Gold Potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces (for speedier spud prep, skip
the peeling). Mince or grate @garlic{2%clove}. Finely chop @parsley{¼%ounce}
leaves and stems.

Toss potatoes on one side of a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of
@vegetable oil{1%tbsp} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. (For 4 servings,
spread potatoes out across entire baking sheet.) Roast on top rack until lightly
browned, ~{10-12%minutes} (we'll add green beans then).

Once potatoes are lightly browned, remove baking sheet from oven and toss
@green beans{6%ounce} on opposite side with a drizzle of oil, salt, pepper, and
garlic. (For 4 servings, leave potatoes roasting and toss green beans on a second
#baking sheet{}; roast on middle rack.) Continue roasting until veggies are
browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes} more.

Once green beans are in the oven, pat @ranch steak{10%ounce} dry with
#paper towels{} and season all over with salt and pepper. Heat a drizzle of
oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add steak and cook to desired
doneness, ~{3-6%minutes} per side. Transfer to a #cutting board{}; let rest
~{5%minutes}.

To small bowl with softened butter, stir in @Dijon mustard{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4
servings; we sent more) and a pinch of parsley. Season with salt and pepper.

Slice steak against the grain; divide between #plates{}. Top steak with herb
butter. Serve with green beans and potatoes on the side. Garnish with remaining
parsley.

> We're taking things to the height of deliciousness with compound butter—that's
> butter mixed with herbs and seasonings. For chefs, this ingredient is the
> ultimate secret weapon, because it's just about the easiest and most
> instantaneous way to sauce up a dish. Here, the stuff is dolloped onto steak to
> make it taste so incredibly rich. But you might find yourself adding it to
> everything once you realize just how good it is.